---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import VariantSwitcher from '../../components/VariantSwitcher';

const kicker =
  'font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--color-muted); margin: 0;';
const h1 =
  'font-family: var(--font-sans); font-weight: 700; font-size: var(--text-4xl); line-height: 1.08; margin: calc(var(--rhythm)*0.5) 0 0;';
const h2 =
  'font-family: var(--font-sans); font-weight: 700; font-size: var(--text-xl); line-height: 1.2; margin: calc(var(--rhythm)*1.5) 0 calc(var(--rhythm)*0.5);';
const p = 'margin: 0 0 var(--rhythm); text-wrap: pretty;';
const mono = 'font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.9em;';
---

<Base title="Why this site looks like this — atassis">
  <VariantSwitcher client:load />
  <article style="max-width: var(--measure-prose); margin: 0 auto; padding: calc(var(--rhythm)*1.2) 1.5rem calc(var(--rhythm)*4);">
    <p style={kicker}>atassis · writing · draft</p>
    <h1 style={h1}>Why this site looks like this</h1>

    <p style={`${p} color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-top: var(--rhythm);`}>
      Most engineers&rsquo; personal sites fail in one of two ways. I built this one the way I
      build systems. Say less. Prove more. Let the structure show itself.
    </p>

    <p style={p}>
      Either they shout &ldquo;passionate, results-driven, world-class&rdquo; (adjectives no one
      can check). Or they&rsquo;re a beige r&eacute;sum&eacute; that could belong to anyone. I
      wanted neither.
    </p>

    <h2 style={h2}>Verify, don&rsquo;t assert</h2>
    <p style={p}>
      The thing I actually do for a living is distrust the happy path. I don&rsquo;t take the
      compiler&rsquo;s word that the output is correct. I check it against a benchmark, a
      gold-set, a byte-identical diff. So this site doesn&rsquo;t ask you to take my word either.
      Every claim carries its receipt: a number, a merged-PR link, a commit.
      &ldquo;16 models baked to reference parity, ASR fully end-to-end on the NPU, kernels open&rdquo; is a sentence you can
      click and verify, not a line you have to believe. If I can&rsquo;t substantiate something, it
      doesn&rsquo;t get the checkmark.
    </p>
    <p style={p}>
      Open a claim and see its proof: that single idea is the spine of the whole site. It&rsquo;s
      the most honest thing I can put on a page, because it&rsquo;s the same move I make in code.
    </p>

    <h2 style={h2}>Invisible craft over visible effort</h2>
    <p style={p}>
      Before designing anything, I read what the technical crowd actually praises, and, more
      usefully, what it mocks. The pattern is brutal and clear: people reward invisible craft
      (typography, speed, restraint) and ridicule visible effort (intro loaders, particle
      backgrounds, custom cursors, scroll-jacking, the obligatory &ldquo;terminal typing&rdquo;
      intro). Anything that announces &ldquo;look what I animated&rdquo; reads as insecurity.
    </p>
    <p style={p}>
      So the aesthetic here is deliberately quiet: warm paper, near-monochrome, one earthy accent,
      almost no motion. The few moving parts are functional, not decorative. Nothing here should
      look like it&rsquo;s trying. Of course, that takes the most trying of all.
    </p>

    <h2 style={h2}>A real type system, not vibes</h2>
    <p style={p}>
      The part I enjoyed most. Good layout isn&rsquo;t about picking a nice font; it&rsquo;s about
      relationships, and relationships should come from a system, not from nudging pixels until it
      &ldquo;looks right.&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p style={p}>
      Everything here derives from a few decisions: a <span style={mono}>modular type scale</span>
      (every size is the base times a fixed ratio), a <span style={mono}>vertical rhythm</span> (all
      spacing is a whole multiple of one baseline unit, so text sits on an invisible grid), one
      spacing scale shared by horizontal and vertical gaps, and a comfortable measure for reading.
      These live as <span style={mono}>design tokens</span>: change the base or the ratio in
      one place and the whole site re-proportions itself, coherently.
    </p>
    <p style={p}>
      While building it I kept a grid overlay I could toggle on (baseline lines and columns
      drawn over the page) to check that things actually land on the grid instead of merely
      looking close. Seeing the rigor is half of getting it right.
    </p>

    <h2 style={h2}>Two sides on one page</h2>
    <p style={p}>
      I write systems, and I write verse. Most advice says to hide the second thing: keep it
      &ldquo;professional.&rdquo; I think that&rsquo;s the wrong instinct for the people I want to
      work with: a real, multidimensional person beats a r&eacute;sum&eacute; avatar. So the poetry
      is here, in Russian, on its own narrower measure and its own serif, so it breathes differently
      than the engineering.
    </p>
    <p style={p}>
      And the &ldquo;open it and see the proof&rdquo; idea extends naturally: a claim opens to its
      receipt; a poem can open to its structure: its meter, an earlier draft of a line. Same
      gesture, two materials. It&rsquo;s the one thing here that only an engineer who is also a poet
      could have made.
    </p>

    <h2 style={h2}>Where it lives</h2>
    <p style={p}>
      Static site, built with Astro, served from GitHub Pages. It never touches my own servers.
      My homelab runs my services; my public face shouldn&rsquo;t be a door into them. It loads
      fast and works without JavaScript for everything that matters. It also degrades gracefully
      where a browser is old.
    </p>

    <p style={`${mono} color: var(--color-muted); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-rule); padding-top: var(--rhythm); margin-top: calc(var(--rhythm)*2);`}>
      <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">&check;</span> this page is the first receipt:
      a site that explains how it was built.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
